    <thetext>&gt; $ ulimit -Ss
&gt; 8192
&gt; 
&gt; $ ulimit -Hs
&gt; unlimited
&gt; 
&gt; $ cat Makefile
&gt; .PHONY: all restart
&gt; 
&gt; all:
&gt; 	ulimit -s
&gt; 
&gt; ifeq ($(MAKE_RESTARTS),)
&gt; Makefile: restart
&gt; 	touch $@
&gt; endif
&gt; 
&gt; $ make
&gt; touch Makefile
&gt; ulimit -s
&gt; unlimited

(This plagues me in LibreOffice development, where make routinely restarts that way, some recipe calls gdb to generate a core backtrace, and gdb runs into infinite recursion on main thread due to &lt;https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=61460#c1&gt; &quot;Demangler crash (GDB PR 17043)&quot;, causing its stack to grow beyond limit and the machine to crawl to a halt.)

There is a fix upstream, &lt;http://git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/make.git/commit/?id=a3d8c086d54c112fecfa2b9026a32a14f741f5f5&gt; &quot;* main.c (main): [SV 48009] Reset stack limit for make re-exec.&quot;, would be great if that could be backported to F24.</thetext>
